  <discussion>Calliergon richardsonii is easily separated from other members of the genus by its comparatively short, usually branched or 2-fid stem leaf costa. The species has smaller alar regions than C. cordifolium and C. giganteum, which aids in separating it from occasional specimens of the other two that have some leaves with a slightly shorter costa than usual. Due to somewhat less spreading branch leaves and a less regular branching pattern, the plants do not become spruce treelike as in C. giganteum. Differences between 5. C. megalophyllum and C. richardsonii are provided with the former. Molecular evidence (M. Stech, pers. comm.) suggests that C. richardsonii consists of two entities, the status of which is currently being investigated.</discussion>
